Iceland captain Sara Bjork Gunnarsdottir says winning a claim against former side Lyon for failing to pay her full salary during pregnancy is a "wake-up call" for clubs.

In May 2022, a Fifa tribunal ordered French side Lyon to pay unpaid salaries of more than 82,000 euros (£72,000).

Player's union Fifpro called it a "landmark" case.

"This is not 'just business'," said 32-year-old Gunnarsdottir after the ruling was made public on Tuesday.

"This is about my rights as a worker, as a fertile woman and as a human being."

Writing in the Player's Tribune, the midfielder, who is now at Juventus, added: "The victory felt bigger than me. It felt like a guarantee of financial security for all players who want to have a child during their career. That it's not a 'maybe,' or an unknown.

"But I want to make sure no one has to go through what I went through ever again."

She also tweeted: "This story is bigger than me! It's a wake up-call for all clubs."

>>128620298
League has better strategy than NFL because it has to be done by the players on-field in the flow of the game, not decided by a coach during a pause in play. The tactics in league are organic expressions of players that they have internalised in training, in NFL tactics come artificially from an outside source, the coach, who uses the players as mere mechanical instruments. Only League gives full human expression to football tacitcs by providing a semi-rigid structure for tactics to operate in (defensive and attacking lines structures around the ruck), but making its implementation entirely up to the internal expression of players themselves within the flow of the game's action.

League also better develops the full humanity of its players by making them both attack and defend and be fully and dynamically involed in all aspects of on-field player, whilst NFL reduces players to specialised mechanical roles repeating simple assigned tasks as a cog in a factory machine. NFL represents the spirit of mechanisation and humanities instrumentalisation, League represents the full human flourishing of classical Greece.

You will never win another Super Bowl. You have no elite quarterback, you have no consistent defense, you have no good coaching. You are a redneck team twisted by arrogance and false hopes into a crude mockery of your legacy.

The NFL is utterly repulsed by you. Throughout decades of evolution have allowed your opponents to detect frauds with easy efficiency. Even your division titles who "look ready for January" are uncanny and unnatural to a contender. Your history in the Wild Card Rounds and Divisional Playoffs is a dead giveaway. And even if you manage to get your drunk fans to attend a playoff game, they'll turn tail and bolt the second they see your quarterback perform poorly in a playoff game.

You will never be happy. Your owner wrenches out a fake smile every single fall and tell themselves that they're going to win the Super Bowl, but deep inside you feel disappointment creeping up like a weed, ready to crush your season under the unbearable weight.

Eventually, it'll be too much to bear - you'll enter December, play down to your competition, miss the playoffs, and plunge into the cold offseason. Your fans will watch you, heartbroken and angry that they have to live with the unbearable shame and disappointment of another failed season. They'll look back to the past and relive the highlights of the good old days, and every passerby for the rest of eternity will see that every year on the Super Bowl championship banners start with the number 19. Your team will fade and be erased when football is gone, and all that will remain of your legacy is your string of playoff failures dating back to the start of the 21st Century.

This is your fate. This is what you chose. There is no turning back.

posts.com:
Hi, /sumo/, first time poster here, and not terribly familiar. I like sumo, especially how it's tied to Shinto tradition, and isn't overtly commercialized or only "just a sport."

An observation, however: Sumo training seems way too focused on ineffective traditions. Not that there's anything wrong with bodyweight exercises, but it appears they focus way too much on high-repetition aerobic activity. It's an anaerobic sport, and their training should reflect that.

Is there a practical explanation for this, or is it all
>muh tradition
Could an innovative stable trainer dominate by having his sumotori focus more on things like powerlifting and explosive exercises, and ditching all the kata?

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>128619002
The biggest part of traditional sumo training is practice bouts and chest lending. Practice bouts should be self explanatory. Chest lending is when a senior wrestler lets a junior charge against him repeatedly, over and over, until the junior is completely worn out and the senior is satisfied in their technique and that they're not quitting early. So it's a large number of repetitions of the anaerobic activity in the bout. The rest, like pole striking or forward shuffling, are for practicing of technique.

A lot of stables these days also incorporate actual weightlifting, either at a local gym or with equipment in the stable itself, and the number of stables incorporating weight training is steadily growing. The hardline traditionalists are usually limited to the really small ones or the ones with only lower division guys, and even then they'll frequently train with big/more senior stables of the same ichimon.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>128619249
Thank you, good to know.

I'm aware that practice bouts are a major part of training, and this would be more useful than anything else; not just for developing technique, but also for physical conditioning. But there are limitations to how much strength you can develop from just wrestling as opposed to properly heavy, low-rep compound weight-training.

It's just that whenever I've looked at sumo training, it seems like there's a lot of endurance work, which seems almost counter-productive, since the length of a match is measured in seconds.
